[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating JSON macro interpolation**\n\nI need to test if a compile-time JSON literal allows comments, which typically aren’t allowed. I'm wondering if the macro replacement placeholder might support string interpolation. Currently, it looks like only the entire JSON values can be interpolated, such as `\"owner\": $owner`. But can the interpolator handle embedded holes in strings, like in Scala interpolation? It seems like I need to check if placeholders can be used within triple-quoted strings and how StringContext interacts with that.\n\n**Exploring JSON interpolation support**\n\nI'm considering whether `json\"\"\" { \"msg\": \"hello $name\" } \"\"\"` supports regular Scala interpolation with placeholder replacements within a JSON string. I'm curious if circe-literal handles this correctly. It seems like placeholder length could depend on its position. When parsing, it looks like the replacement class applies to whole values and keys. I want to test if placeholders within strings might work too. Would the macro substitute these correctly? What if the placeholder is unchanged? It could be unsupported, so I need to check the documentation for details.\n\n**Planning code exploration**\n\nI'm thinking about creating a compile snippet in my mind but not actually running tests. It seems like I could use the Scala compiler, but I should avoid compiling or executing tests directly. Maybe I can use `javap` for some exploratory purposes instead. I wonder if I can inspect the macro bytecode with a decompiler like CFR. I might proceed with `javap -c` to inspect the compiled code. This way, I can explore without executing anything.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_027cc18958f3bb65016a3f75f4fb748193be167a1f4299342f\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqP3X_EgssLt7IFFyPsoQCLhAxah42WUjXJCuJP9w6yQuOilyujICHV7p4fJYHu_VbIpU30d6xt394Mr47